title: For Sale:  Vortex Diamondback HP 4-16x42 with flip covers
postcontent: The price for the scope is $300 or I will do $325 with the Burris PEPR mount if you want it.  The Burris mount is not available for $25 alone I'm simply offering that to sweeten the deal for someone needing an entire setup.  Bougth in December 2016 for my hog rifle, but have since gone to all night hog hunting with a thermal which has it's own proprietary mounting system.  This is the BDC reticle.  Fantastic glass with a lifetime warranty.  Also comes with Vortex Defender flip covers, screw on sun shade, box, manual and an extra set of bungee covers.  Pics show a Burris PEPR mount which is for sale separately, but if you want that too I'll do $325 for the scope and mount.  If you decide to buy the Vortex with the Burris I mount my scopes with painstaking precision and utilize a process that takes inevitable manufacturing tolerances out of the equation.  Most people use a level/level/level approach and make a huge assumption when they place a bubble level on top of the elevation turret that the reticle has been stamped dead square on the lens with respect to the elevation turret top surface.  This is rarely the case and why so many people struggle with accuracy as they shoot longer and longer....yes even when you pay a gunsmith/rifle tech at your favorite dealer to do it they make this assumption when mounting b/c it's quick and easy and will suffice for most shooters.  If all you do is shoot 100 yards or less you can get by with your elevation line askew a bit, but by the time you step out to 300 yards with most calibers and begin with hold overs or turret tracking the problems will arise quickly.  The only way to ensure *your* reticle is dead square on the lens with respect to leveling all other aspects of the rifle for mounting is to shine a flashlight backwards through the objective lens onto the wall and use a plumb bob.  I've tweaked a couple of scopes this way for friends who could never get their turrets to track properly at long range all because their reticle wasn't pefectly flush and square to the turret top they leveled it to(one of them was a $2,500 Carl Zeiss so it's a potential problem in any scope put together by imperfect humans).  This Vortex is dead nuts square.Cash only and pick up only please at my home.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Beautiful Lone Star made Remington Rolling Block Reproduction
postcontent: For sale is a Rolling Block rifle w/ a 32" octagonal barrel and chambered in 45/90 (I shot 45/70 through because of cost but you can shoot 45/90) made by the legendary David Higgenbotham of Conroe, TX.  He had a company called Lone Star Rifle Company.  He started making guns around 1993-1994 and made them until his untimely passing in 2011.  It seems that nobody really knows how many of these guns were made.  I've seen serial numbers up to 430 mentioned in various forums online.  This one has a serial number of 289.  The previous owner used it to shoot at camp Perry at targets out to 1000 yards.  These are some of the best reproduction rolling blocks ever made.  I've seen them for sale online for $2500+.  As you can see in the pictures, this one is flawed, but only in appearance.  It functions perfectly.  The previous owner didn't like the pearl inlays that the original owner had put in the butt stock so he cut them out and replaced them with a wood patch that closely matches the original wood.  He didn't do a bad job though I wish he would have left it original.  This just gives it more charactrer I guess.Also, there is no rear tang ladder sight on the gun.  It does have the nice front globe sight but it needs a new tang sight in the rear.  You can buy reproductions online that very from $200-400 dollars.  Some even more if you want to spend that kind of money for a tang sight.  Or, occasionally you can find a real one from an original gun online but they are even more expensive.So, knowing that the gun is without its fairly expensive rear tang sight plus the fact that it has the patches in the stock, I am pricing it at a very reasonable $950 obo.  These guns are going to continue to go up in value do to there rarety.  I am selling it because I have decided I want to focus more on WWI and WWII guns......nothing older than that.
